Medieval Universities Create the Modern Intellectual
The thoughts of Aristotle and Plato were largely forgotten in the “Dark” and Middle Ages in Europe, but the creation of narrative history continued to flourish.
The Middle Ages were formative in the birth of the university as we know it.
The university had certain autonomy for the first time from existing political, religious, and economic institutions.
University degrees and intellectual thought (e.g., philosophy) became valuable in their own right, and the rise of the professor as a career was born.
